# Natural numbers: definition

Axiom.  There exists a type ‚Ñï (the natural numbers) with an element 0 : ‚Ñï and a function s : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚Ñï such that

  a. There is no n : ‚Ñï such that s(n) = 0.  [0 is not successor]
  b. For all n, m : ‚Ñï, if s(n) = s(m) then n = m.  [succ is injective]
  c. Let P : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ùîπ.  If 0 ‚àà P, and k ‚àà P implies s(k) ‚àà P for all k : ‚Ñï, then P = ‚Ñï.  [induction]

Definition.  Let 1 : ‚Ñï = s(0).

Theorem.  Let x : ‚Ñï.  Suppose that x ‚â† 0.  Then there is some y : ‚Ñï such that x = s(y).   [positive is successor]

Theorem.  For all x : ‚Ñï, s(x) ‚â† x.  [all x ‚â† s(x)]

# Addition

Axiom.  There is a binary operation + : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚Ñï ‚Üí ‚Ñï such that for all x, y : ‚Ñï,

  a. x + 0 = x.
  b. x + s(y) = s(x + y).

Lemma.  For all x, y ‚àà ‚Ñï, x + (y + 0) = (x + y) + 0.

Theorem (associativity of addition).  For all x, y, z : ‚Ñï,

    x + (y + z) = (x + y) + z.

Lemma.

    a. For all x ‚àà ‚Ñï, 0 + x = x.  [zero left sum]
    b. For all x, y ‚àà ‚Ñï, s(x) + y = s(x + y).

Theorem (commutativity of addition).  For all x, y : ‚Ñï,

    x + y = y + x.

Theorem (cancellation law for addition).  For all x, y, z : ‚Ñï,

    x + z = y + z implies x = y.

Theorem.  For all x, y : ‚Ñï, y ‚â† s(x) + y.   [add successor distinct]

# Ordering

Definition.  For all x, y ‚àà ‚Ñï, x < y iff there is some z ‚àà ‚Ñï such that x + s(z) = y.

Theorem.  Let x, y, z ‚àà ‚Ñï.

    a. x ‚âÆ x.     [irreflexivity of <]
    b. x < y and y < z implies x < z.  [transitivity of <]

Proof.

    a. Suppose that x < x.  Then there is some z : ‚Ñï such that x + s(z) = x.  But x + s(z) ‚â† x by [add successor distinct] and [commutativity of addition].  This is a contradiction.

    b. Suppose that x < y and y < z.  Then there exist u, v : ‚Ñï such that x + s(u) = y and y + s(v) = z.  Then

        z = (x + s(u)) + s(v)
           = x + (s(u) + s(v))
           = x + s(u + s(v)).
    
    So x < z.

Theorem (trichotomy).  Let x, y: ‚Ñï.  Precisely one of x < y or x = y or y < x holds.

Proof.

If x < y and x = y then x < x, contradicting [irreflexivity of <].  If x = y and y < x, then x < x, again contradicting [irreflexivity of <].  If x < y and y < x then by [transitivity of <] we have x < x, contradicting [irreflexivity of <].

We will now prove that x < y or x = y or y < x.  Let A = { x : ‚Ñï | x < y or x = y or y < x }.  We must prove that A = ‚Ñï.  First, by [positive is successor] we have either y = 0, or y = s(u) for some u : ‚Ñï.  Hence by [zero left sum] either y = 0, or 0 + s(u) = y for some u : ‚Ñï.  So y = 0 or 0 < y.  Thus 0 ‚àà A.

Now assume that v ‚àà A.  Then v < y or v = y or y < v.

Suppose that v < y.  Then v + s(z) = y for some z : ‚Ñï.  By [positive is successor], either z = 0, or z = s(u) for some u : ‚Ñï.  If z = 0 then v + 1 = y, that is s(v) = y.

# Theorem.  For all x : ‚Ñï, there is no y : ‚Ñï such that x < y < s(x).  [‚Ñï is discrete]

# Proof.  Let x : ‚Ñï, and assume there is some y : ‚Ñï such that x < y < s(x).  By [less if add succ] there is some u : ‚Ñï such that x + s(u) = y.  Now s(x) + u = x + s(u) = y.  So s(x) ‚â§ y.  But we know that y < s(x).  This is a contradiction to [trichotomy].

