# # Well-ordering principle

# Definition.  For all S : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ùîπ, S is empty iff there is no n : ‚Ñï such that n ‚àà S.  S is nonempty iff S is not empty.

# Definition.  For all A : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ùîπ and a : ‚Ñï, a is a least element of A iff a ‚àà A and for all x : ‚Ñï, if x ‚àà A then a ‚â§ x.

# Theorem (well-ordering principle). Let A : ‚Ñï ‚Üí ùîπ.  Suppose that A is nonempty.  Then there exists some x : ‚Ñï such that x is a least element of A.

# Proof.  Assume there is no x : ‚Ñï such that x is a least element of A.  Let

#         B = { x ‚àà ‚Ñï | for all u ‚àà ‚Ñï, if u ‚â§ x then u ‚àâ A }.

# Assume that 0 ‚àâ B.  Then there is some u : ‚Ñï such that u ‚â§ 0 and u ‚àà A.  Then u = 0 by [nonzero is positive].  Thus 0 ‚àà A.  But then 0 is a least element of A, which is a contradiction.  Hence 0 ‚àà B.

# Let x ‚àà B.  Then for all u : ‚Ñï, if u ‚â§ x then u ‚àâ A.  Assume that s(x) ‚àà A.  Then by [‚Ñï is discrete] s(x) is a least element of A, which is a contradiction.  So s(x) ‚àâ A.
